{"id":"george-washington-memorial-parkway","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"George Washington Memorial Parkway","revisionId":1361004137,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Washington_Memorial_Parkway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Washington_Memorial_Parkway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"George Washington Memorial Parkway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Washington_Memorial_Parkway","revisionId":1361004137,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Mount Vernon, VA","to":"McLean, VA","via":["City of Alexandria, VA","Long Bridge Park, VA","North Highland, VA"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Mount Vernon","state":"VA","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":2.7,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Washington"],"lat":38.81527,"lng":-77.04478,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Fort Hunt","state":"VA","kind":"town","mileFromStart":2.7,"toNextMi":5.7,"note":"Junction toward Fort Hunt Park","control":["Fort Hunt Park"],"lat":38.81527,"lng":-77.04478,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Hunting Creek","state":"VA","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":8.4,"toNextMi":0.5,"note":"","control":[],"lat":38.81527,"lng":-77.04478,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"City of Alexandria","state":"VA","kind":"town","mileFromStart":8.9,"toNextMi":3.2,"note":"Junction toward RichmondModule:Jct error: Invalid \"to\" argument","control":["RichmondModule:Jct error: Invalid \"to\" argument","First Street","Abingdon Drive"],"lat":38.8208,"lng":-77.04404,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":5,"place":"Four Mile Run","state":"VA","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":12.1,"toNextMi":0.4,"note":"Junction toward Bridge","control":["Bridge"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":6,"place":"Crystal City","state":"VA","kind":"town","mileFromStart":12.5,"toNextMi":1.8,"note":"Junction toward Reagan National Airport","control":["Reagan National Airport"],"lat":38.85098,"lng":-77.04767,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":7,"place":"Long Bridge Park","state":"VA","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":14.3,"toNextMi":0.4,"note":"Junction toward Richmond & Washington","control":["Richmond","Washington"],"lat":38.87076,"lng":-77.04143,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":8,"place":"Columbia Island","state":"VA","kind":"town","mileFromStart":14.7,"toNextMi":1.4,"note":"Junction toward Arlington Cemetery","control":["Arlington Cemetery","LBJ Memorial Grove","Pentagon"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":9,"place":"Rosslyn","state":"VA","kind":"park-entrance","mileFromStart":16.1,"toNextMi":1.3,"note":"Junction toward Washington & Rosslyn","control":["Washington","Rosslyn"],"lat":38.89766,"lng":-77.06808,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":10,"place":"North Highland","state":"VA","kind":"park-entrance","mileFromStart":17.4,"toNextMi":4.1,"note":"Junction toward Washington","control":["Washington"],"lat":38.90143,"lng":-77.08196,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":11,"place":"McLean","state":"VA","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":21.5,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Washington","McLean","George Bush Center for Intelligence","CIA","FHWA","Turkey Run Park","Virginia"],"lat":38.81557,"lng":-77.04471,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["The trip by DC area residents to see George Washington's family estate at Mount Vernon was seen in the late 19th and early 20th centuries as a patriotic duty as well as an opportunity to learn about American history and democratic values. In the late 19th century, most people took a steamboat excursion from DC (it also made a stop in Alexandria). By the 1920s, 200,000 people a year were visiting Mount Vernon.","In the 1880s, officials in Alexandria, Virginia, attempted to boost local commerce by advocating for a \"national road\" to Mount Vernon. They formed the Mount Vernon Avenue Association in September 1887, to promote this idea. Congress appropriated $10,000 for a survey in 1889. The United States Army Corps of Engineers conducted the survey, and in its report agreed that a superior, no-expense-spared road from Alexandria to Mount Vernon was necessary. However, construction of the Washington, Alexandria, and Mount Vernon Railway (an inexpensive commuter trolley/streetcar system) between 1892 and 1896 dealt a serious blow to the plan.","During the Alexandria Sesquicentennial in 1899, several Alexandria civic boosters called for a bridge to be built between Alexandria and Washington, DC. This reignited interest in a roadway to Mount Vernon. The idea generated interest among many of the individuals active in the City Beautiful movement, Colonial Revival architecture movement, and groups dedicated to promoting local and national history. Soon, the idea of a roadway became a call for a grandiose, monumental avenue lined with Beaux-Arts memorials, tombs, and roadside attractions. The idea received even more impetus when the Daughters of the American Revolution took up the cause. In 1902, the McMillan Plan endorsed a road along the Virginia side of the Potomac River shoreline. Although Virginia was outside the plan's scope, the Senate Park Commission (which drafted the plan) saw a Mount Vernon avenue as an extension of the DC park system as well as a means of protecting the Great Falls of the Potomac River and the Potomac Palisades. The McMillan Plan, however, focused not on a monumental avenue but on tree-lined boulevards and quiet carriage paths designed to relax and calm.","The Mount Vernon Avenue Association disbanded some time during World War I, but the concept of a Mount Vernon roadway was now championed by the federal Bureau of Public Roads (BPR). The BPR seized on the idea in the 1920s as a means of demonstrating the latest highway construction technology. Its first proposals were merely to upgrade the existing roads in the area and perhaps add a tree-lined boulevard, with formal, uninspired masonry bridges. But the BPR's proposals quickly evolved into much more. The agency hired Gilmore David Clarke and Jay Downer, who had designed the highly celebrated Central Westchester Parkway in New York, as consultants. They quickly proposed a more elaborate system of plantings, historic roadside pullouts, and scenic overlooks, and a more sinuous road design. The BPR began calling the road a \"highway\" rather than a parkway to de-emphasize its commemorative nature in the hope that Congress would fund its construction."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Mount Vernon","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Mount Vernon","lat":38.73527778,"lng":-77.09527778,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Hunting Creek","d":"A landmark on the route","q":"Hunting Creek","lat":38.78967778,"lng":-77.05067222,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Long Bridge Park","d":"Junction toward Richmond & Washington","q":"Long Bridge Park","lat":38.87111111,"lng":-77.04083333,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Rosslyn","d":"Junction toward Washington & Rosslyn","q":"Rosslyn","lat":38.89666667,"lng":-77.0725,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"North Highland","d":"Junction toward Washington","q":"North Highland","lat":38.8981673,"lng":-77.0830335,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"\"George Washington Memorial Parkway\" (Map). Google Maps. Retrieved October 4, 2013.","url":"https://www.google.com/maps/preview#!data=!1m4!1m3!1d5259!2d-77.1793916!3d38.964259!4m21!3m20!1m4!3m2!3d38.7107439!